summary: On Crowley’s side of things, seeing Aziraphale so entangled in his essentialist beliefs must be torture. He loves the angel, the...
body:
On Crowley’s side of things, seeing Aziraphale so entangled in his essentialist beliefs must be torture. He loves the angel, the angel loves him, but as long as Aziraphale hasn’t been able to free himself from this line of thinking, he would never do nor admit anything about it.
So, yes, maybe Crowley could have helped him getting rid off his beliefs a bit more actively ( 6000 years is a bit too long, even for immortal beings… ). But with that comes the risk of making the other one angry, or making him shut down completely. Challenging someone’s beliefs, even when these beliefs are obviously wrong and harmful, is a delicate and dangerous thing to do.
And Aziraphale is Crowley’s only friend. He is the only one that matters. Crowley couldn’t risk loosing this relationship.
Therefore, even if that means having a stagnating relationship for all eternity, Crowley is so terrified he might lose Aziraphale that he would never take the first step or challenge his beliefs too strongly.

title: A Novak Dilemma
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2HSRWx3

by Botanist (aesthalien), Forever_Ours_98 (Double_Trouble_Account)

The host, James Novak is arrested for the crime of child abuse and rape of his daughter, Claire, and was accused of doing this for several years.

James has different personalities residing within him, and in court he was filed insane, he was sentenced to 3 and a half years in a mental institution instead of a prison. He has to visit a therapist every week until the end of his punishment.

Every personality has a different version of the same incident, these are their stories.
